    "reading": {
      "anchor": "A&amp;G §47 · Nominative case",
      "title": "The Nominative Case",
      "blocks": [
        { "type": "p", "html": "The nominative is the case of the <span class=\"alph-resources__em\">subject</span>. The subject of a finite verb is in the nominative case, denoting the person or thing that performs the action of the verb, or that is in the state described by the verb. <a class=\"alph-resources__crossref\" href=\"#\">See §340 for predicate nominative.</a>" },
        { "type": "blockquote", "html": "<span class=\"lang-classical\">Mīlitēs in castra revertuntur.</span><br />The soldiers return to camp." },
        { "type": "p", "html": "Some Latin nouns are used predominantly or exclusively in the plural — these are called <span class=\"alph-resources__em\">pluralia tantum</span>. <span class=\"lang-classical\" style=\"font-style:italic;\">Arma</span>, <em>weapons</em>, is one such noun: in classical prose and verse it appears almost exclusively in the plural, the singular being a rare reconstruction." }
      ]
    },
